50|$|Sida cordifolia (ilima, flannel weed, bala, <b>country</b> <b>mallow</b> or heart-leaf sida) is a {{perennial}} subshrub of the mallow family Malvaceae native to India. It has naturalized throughout the world, {{and is considered}} an invasive weed in Africa, Australia, the southern United States, Hawaiian Islands, New Guinea, and French Polynesia. The specific name, cordifolia, refers to the heart-shaped leaf.|$|E

